{
  "texts": [
    "Together with the fact that P(E i,j) = 1 2, this completes the proof.Proof of Theorem 2.",
    "We continue with the notations established in Lemmas 2 and 3.",
    "LetX = {x i,j } ∈ R N ×p, x i:= (x i,0,..., x i,p-1) i.i.d.∼ N (0, Σ), and denote the frequency-domain representation by Y ∈ C N ×p.",
    "Then for each row, the effective entries satisfy:ℑ(y t) = - 1 √ p p-1 n=0x n sin(θ t,n), where θ t,n = 2πtn p. Let s t denotes (sin(θ t,0),..., sin(θ t,p-1)) ∈ R 1×p.",
    "Since each x i is Gaussian, ℑ(y t) is Gaussian with zero mean andVar [ℑ(y t)] = 1 p s ⊤ t Σs ∈ λ min p ∥s t ∥ 2 2, λ max p ∥s t ∥ 2 2 = λ min 2, λ max 2,where ∥s t ∥ 2 2 = p 2 follows from Lemma 2 and λ min and λ max denote the smallest and largest eigenvalue of the covariance matrix Σ, respectively.Given a pseudorandom bit ζ t ∈ {0, 1}, the process of watermark embedding in Algorithm 1 replaces ℑ(y t) byℑ (y wm t) = -δ • ℑ(y t), if ℑ(y t) • (2ζ t -1) < 0 and |ℑ(y t)| ≤ Quantile γ ({|ℑ(y t)|} m t=1), ℑ (y t), otherwise, Let α t:= ℑ(y wm t), λ 2:= Var ℑ(y t) ∈ λ min 2, λ max 2,and defineF (x):= 2 √ πλ e -x 2 λ I(x ≥ 0), F δ (x):= 2 δ √ πλ exp - x 2 δ 2 λ I(x ≥ 0),which are the PDFs of α t and δ α t, respectively."
  ]
